23
00:01:28,260 --> 00:01:31,298
Berlin is never Berlin,

24
00:01:31,332 --> 00:01:33,403
they say.

25
00:01:33,438 --> 00:01:37,442
Pounded into rubble by Allied
bombs and Russian artillery

26
00:01:37,476 --> 00:01:39,340
in World War II,

27
00:01:39,375 --> 00:01:41,204
surrounded,

28
00:01:41,239 --> 00:01:44,311
then hacked in two
during the Cold War,

29
00:01:44,345 --> 00:01:46,934
then reunited and reborn,

30
00:01:46,968 --> 00:01:50,593
Berlin is a city of ghosts.

31
00:01:50,627 --> 00:01:52,595
An ever-evolving space

32
00:01:52,629 --> 00:01:55,943
where memories and new ideas

33
00:01:55,977 --> 00:01:58,773
live side by side.

34
00:01:58,808 --> 00:01:59,308
♪

35
00:02:07,541 --> 00:02:09,543
In between and after the wars,

36
00:02:09,577 --> 00:02:12,511
Berlin has always been a place
where you find what you want

37
00:02:12,546 --> 00:02:15,307
or what you think you need,

38
00:02:15,342 --> 00:02:16,722
what you can't get back home.

39
00:02:19,000 --> 00:02:22,659
A place where fantasies
could come true.

40
00:02:22,694 --> 00:02:26,974
It's all here,
if you know where to look.

41
00:02:30,253 --> 00:02:31,979
It's no coincidence,

42
00:02:32,013 --> 00:02:34,188
it's a natural progression,
really,

43
00:02:34,223 --> 00:02:36,328
that Berlin's nightlife
is excessive,

44
00:02:36,363 --> 00:02:38,296
completely and proudly
uninhibited,

45
00:02:38,330 --> 00:02:39,883
and never-ending.

46
00:02:42,023 --> 00:02:44,198
There are clubs for everybody

47
00:02:44,233 --> 00:02:45,993
and many are friendly towards

48
00:02:46,027 --> 00:02:50,239
whatever your personal
lifestyle choices might be.

49
00:02:50,273 --> 00:02:52,241
Club culture is the pride
of Berliners

50
00:02:52,275 --> 00:02:54,312
and draws millions
of thrill seekers

51
00:02:54,346 --> 00:02:56,210
from all over the world.

52
00:02:56,245 --> 00:02:58,695
It is notoriously difficult
to navigate, however,

53
00:02:58,730 --> 00:03:01,664
and finding the right place
with the right mix

54
00:03:01,698 --> 00:03:04,011
that will actually
let you in the door

55
00:03:04,045 --> 00:03:05,392
can be a challenge.

56
00:03:05,426 --> 00:03:06,910
♪

57
00:03:06,945 --> 00:03:09,223
Who decides who gets in,

58
00:03:09,258 --> 00:03:11,225
keeps each place
with its own personal,

59
00:03:11,260 --> 00:03:13,020
non-judgmental balance

60
00:03:13,054 --> 00:03:16,851
are people like Frank Kunster.

61
00:03:16,886 --> 00:03:20,683
For 25 years, he's been
the gatekeeper and bouncer

62
00:03:20,717 --> 00:03:23,720
at some of Berlin's
most infamous club doorways.

63
00:03:23,755 --> 00:03:24,255
♪

64
00:03:30,555 --> 00:03:34,421
You were described
as a legendary doorman.

65
00:03:34,455 --> 00:03:36,043
Yeah, maybe.

66
00:03:36,077 --> 00:03:38,528
Older?

67
00:03:38,563 --> 00:03:42,808
Well, the... the last three
years at [indistinct] bar.

68
00:03:42,843 --> 00:03:44,638
Right.

69
00:03:44,672 --> 00:03:46,295
A professional partier

70
00:03:46,329 --> 00:03:49,919
in Berlin, what time do they
show up at the club?

71
00:03:49,953 --> 00:03:51,403
6:00 in
the morning.

72
00:03:51,438 --> 00:03:52,646
- No way.
- Oh, yes, of course.

73
00:03:52,680 --> 00:03:54,648
So wait a minute,
you arrive at 6:00 am.

74
00:03:54,682 --> 00:03:58,410
And then the clubs,
they go from Saturday evening

75
00:03:58,445 --> 00:04:00,619
to Monday morning
without any break.

76
00:04:00,654 --> 00:04:03,484
So people go there normally
Sunday morning

77
00:04:03,519 --> 00:04:06,073
and then they dance Sunday
all day and all night,

78
00:04:06,107 --> 00:04:07,557
then go home Monday morning.

79
00:04:07,592 --> 00:04:09,939
So you're talking 24 hours.

80
00:04:09,973 --> 00:04:11,561
No, 36 hours, no problem.

81
00:04:11,596 --> 00:04:13,563
36 hours. What are you
doing for 36 hours?

82
00:04:13,598 --> 00:04:15,910
Dancing, talking, chilling,

83
00:04:15,945 --> 00:04:18,982
hugging, [...]ing,
whatever.

84
00:04:19,017 --> 00:04:21,640
I don't want to do any of
those things for 36 hours

85
00:04:21,675 --> 00:04:24,678
personally, I think.

86
00:04:24,712 --> 00:04:26,335
Danke.

87
00:04:32,858 --> 00:04:35,654
Um, I have to begin, sir.

88
00:04:35,689 --> 00:04:39,486
Beautiful.

89
00:04:39,520 --> 00:04:43,455
As a large man with
a physically challenging job,

90
00:04:43,490 --> 00:04:45,354
Frank likes meat,

91
00:04:45,388 --> 00:04:46,424
as I do.

92
00:04:46,458 --> 00:04:49,427
So a long-established
butcher shop

93
00:04:49,461 --> 00:04:51,463
like Fleischerie Domke

94
00:04:51,498 --> 00:04:54,121
is just what
the both of us need.

95
00:04:54,155 --> 00:04:54,655
♪

96
00:04:58,815 --> 00:05:02,371
Pork schnitzel with murky,
delicious brown gravy,

97
00:05:02,405 --> 00:05:05,788
and boulette, which I gather
is German for meatballs,

98
00:05:05,822 --> 00:05:08,653
is the kind of working-class
food one wants

99
00:05:08,687 --> 00:05:12,139
and needs.

100
00:05:12,173 --> 00:05:15,832
So what attracted you
to this business?

101
00:05:15,867 --> 00:05:18,490
The night had always, like...

102
00:05:18,525 --> 00:05:20,975
I always was...

103
00:05:21,010 --> 00:05:23,633
attracted to the night.

104
00:05:23,668 --> 00:05:25,566
I think people in the night

105
00:05:25,601 --> 00:05:27,982
when they are on alcohol
or on drugs

106
00:05:28,017 --> 00:05:30,640
open their mind.

107
00:05:30,675 --> 00:05:33,643
Because it's dark, they
are more free in their mind.

108
00:05:33,678 --> 00:05:36,853
I found that interesting.

109
00:05:36,888 --> 00:05:41,030
Berlin is world-famous
for its club scene.

110
00:05:41,064 --> 00:05:42,480
Why here?

111
00:05:42,514 --> 00:05:46,449
I think because we are
the last liberal city,

112
00:05:46,484 --> 00:05:48,693
like real liberal, you know?

113
00:05:48,727 --> 00:05:51,420
The people can afford being
here, it's cheap to drink,

114
00:05:51,454 --> 00:05:54,423
it's cheap to live,
it's cheap to eat,

115
00:05:54,457 --> 00:05:57,598
and people come here because
of the freedom to party,

116
00:05:57,633 --> 00:06:01,568
to get wasted
as hard as possible.

117
00:06:01,602 --> 00:06:03,846
How about the police
and the government at this time?

118
00:06:03,880 --> 00:06:06,020
You know, you've got thousands
of people taking ecstasy

119
00:06:06,055 --> 00:06:08,195
and dancing all night till
11:00, 12:00 the next night.

120
00:06:08,229 --> 00:06:09,886
I think the government know...

121
00:06:09,921 --> 00:06:12,406
I know policemen

122
00:06:12,441 --> 00:06:14,408
and they know about, like,
people doing drugs

123
00:06:14,443 --> 00:06:16,755
and they come to our clubs
to do drugs by themselves

124
00:06:16,790 --> 00:06:18,447
or not or they drink,

125
00:06:18,481 --> 00:06:21,898
but they accept
and everybody's cool with it.

126
00:06:21,933 --> 00:06:23,866
Berlin is a party city.

127
00:06:23,900 --> 00:06:26,869
It's no real industry
besides a party industry

128
00:06:26,903 --> 00:06:30,562
and so, so many tourists come
here only because of that

129
00:06:30,597 --> 00:06:32,046
from Spain, from Italy,
from Russia,

130
00:06:32,081 --> 00:06:33,531
from U.S.,
from U.K.

131
00:06:33,565 --> 00:06:36,154
to get totally lost
and totally wasted

132
00:06:36,188 --> 00:06:38,052
but not in a bad way,

133
00:06:38,087 --> 00:06:39,916
just like in a Buddhistic way.

134
00:06:39,951 --> 00:06:43,886
It's like in the moment you get
lost you can find yourself,

135
00:06:43,920 --> 00:06:48,718
and that I think
what excess is about.

136
00:06:48,753 --> 00:06:51,859
Pure hedonism.

137
00:06:53,723 --> 00:06:55,725
Come to Berlin, get high, party.

138
00:06:55,760 --> 00:06:57,589
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

139
00:07:10,568 --> 00:07:12,604
♪

140
00:07:12,639 --> 00:07:13,916
The Wall.

141
00:07:13,950 --> 00:07:17,264
An absurd, tragic,
almost metaphoric,

142
00:07:17,298 --> 00:07:18,990
but all-too-real expression

143
00:07:19,024 --> 00:07:21,820
of humanity's failure
and depravity.

144
00:07:21,855 --> 00:07:25,755
A 96-mile stretch of concrete
and razor wire

145
00:07:25,790 --> 00:07:28,931
cut Berlin into an island
of capitalistic West

146
00:07:28,965 --> 00:07:34,488
and gray, soul-crushing,
repressive communist East.

147
00:07:34,523 --> 00:07:37,491
They keep
a few chunks of it around,

148
00:07:37,526 --> 00:07:39,700
a reminder of terror,
of triumph,

149
00:07:39,735 --> 00:07:43,566
or simply to take selfies
in front of.

150
00:07:43,601 --> 00:07:47,501
Every day
fewer and fewer remember

151
00:07:47,536 --> 00:07:51,022
that the world almost ended

152
00:07:51,056 --> 00:07:52,126
right here.

153
00:07:55,164 --> 00:07:57,511
♪

154
00:07:57,546 --> 00:07:59,133
Even as the wall fell,

155
00:07:59,168 --> 00:08:01,653
techno music seemed to
express something

156
00:08:01,688 --> 00:08:03,793
that needed to be expressed.

157
00:08:03,828 --> 00:08:06,831
Dance music and ecstasy
and mammoth nightclubs

158
00:08:06,865 --> 00:08:11,007
exploded across
a reunited Berlin.

159
00:08:11,042 --> 00:08:12,319
During that time,

160
00:08:12,353 --> 00:08:15,529
DJs like Ellen Allien

161
00:08:15,564 --> 00:08:17,013
were pioneers of the new sound

162
00:08:17,048 --> 00:08:18,567
and a new generation.

163
00:08:18,601 --> 00:08:19,982
♪

164
00:08:20,016 --> 00:08:24,158
East and West, a unifying force.

165
00:08:24,193 --> 00:08:27,852
♪

166
00:08:31,200 --> 00:08:33,236
Sausage is my favorite food.

167
00:08:33,271 --> 00:08:35,825
As a German, you need sausage.

168
00:08:35,860 --> 00:08:37,931
Mm.

169
00:08:37,965 --> 00:08:39,588
Yeah, it's... it's good.

170
00:08:39,622 --> 00:08:40,692
Mm, very good with apple

171
00:08:40,727 --> 00:08:44,696
and, I think.

172
00:08:44,731 --> 00:08:46,698
Lunch at Michelburger,

173
00:08:46,733 --> 00:08:49,252
a joint on Friedrichshain.

174
00:08:52,290 --> 00:08:56,087
♪

175
00:08:56,121 --> 00:08:58,745
Sausage of chicken,
pig's feet, and sage

176
00:08:58,779 --> 00:09:01,575
with smoked mashed potatoes
and apple.

177
00:09:01,610 --> 00:09:04,716
Beef shoulder braised and
served with root vegetables,

178
00:09:04,751 --> 00:09:06,925
potatoes, horseradish,
and, God help me,

179
00:09:06,960 --> 00:09:09,928
kale.

180
00:09:09,963 --> 00:09:12,586
When did the Wall come down?
That was what year?

181
00:09:12,621 --> 00:09:13,691
- '89.
- '89.

182
00:09:13,725 --> 00:09:15,244
So everything started in '89.

183
00:09:15,278 --> 00:09:16,383
Everything started in '89.

184
00:09:16,417 --> 00:09:18,212
First, the club scene

185
00:09:18,247 --> 00:09:20,767
was based on the...
On the West side

186
00:09:20,801 --> 00:09:22,769
where the first
techno club opened.

187
00:09:22,803 --> 00:09:25,944
Wall came down and then
everything moved to the East

188
00:09:25,979 --> 00:09:29,741
because there was space,
a lot of industrial places,

189
00:09:29,776 --> 00:09:32,641
and music was a meeting point
of the East and West

190
00:09:32,675 --> 00:09:35,782
and a meeting point of young
people trying to move together.

191
00:09:35,816 --> 00:09:37,715
It just happened in the club.

192
00:09:37,749 --> 00:09:40,407
When the Wall came down, it was
our music to come together,

193
00:09:40,441 --> 00:09:43,410
so it's very deeply
in our blood.

194
00:09:43,444 --> 00:09:45,239
Right.

195
00:09:45,274 --> 00:09:46,371
That's why it's
so strong for me,

196
00:09:46,378 --> 00:09:47,966
so being a DJ,

197
00:09:48,001 --> 00:09:52,695
because this time was a very
strong impact for my soul.

198
00:09:56,665 --> 00:09:57,165
♪

199
00:10:01,152 --> 00:10:03,430
Over time,

200
00:10:03,464 --> 00:10:06,088
so many artists, musicians,

201
00:10:06,122 --> 00:10:08,642
writers

202
00:10:08,677 --> 00:10:10,851
from elsewhere
have come to Berlin.

203
00:10:10,886 --> 00:10:15,684
It's always been sort of
a magnet for artists

204
00:10:15,718 --> 00:10:17,858
for a lot of reasons.

205
00:10:17,893 --> 00:10:20,274
Why do you think
here of all places

206
00:10:20,309 --> 00:10:22,345
would be so welcoming

207
00:10:22,380 --> 00:10:25,279
and attractive to
creative people?

208
00:10:25,314 --> 00:10:28,282
I think after the second war
everything was burned here.

209
00:10:28,317 --> 00:10:29,801
There was nothing.

210
00:10:29,836 --> 00:10:33,287
Nothing was here, only like
broken stones, you know.

211
00:10:33,322 --> 00:10:37,360
Everything was gone,
all the history.

212
00:10:37,395 --> 00:10:41,951
So people start building up
the new Berlin or whatever

213
00:10:41,986 --> 00:10:44,333
and we are still in that
process, you know,

214
00:10:44,367 --> 00:10:46,887
and when you come here you
have... you have the feeling

215
00:10:46,922 --> 00:10:50,684
that you have to help
to build something here.

216
00:10:50,719 --> 00:10:52,375
I'm a part of it.

217
00:10:52,410 --> 00:10:55,033
If I go to Paris, I'm not
thinking I'm a part of Paris.

218
00:10:55,068 --> 00:10:57,346
I'm not, because there is
so much history

219
00:10:57,380 --> 00:10:58,830
you can see, or Rome...
Right.

220
00:10:58,865 --> 00:11:00,487
I think only about
the Rome history.

221
00:11:00,521 --> 00:11:02,006
- Yes.
- 'Cause there's everything

222
00:11:02,040 --> 00:11:04,318
you can touch.
It's an open air museum, yeah.

223
00:11:04,353 --> 00:11:07,183
But here, you have to feel
you're building something.

224
00:11:07,218 --> 00:11:09,738
I think that's why
so many people come here.

225
00:11:09,772 --> 00:11:13,189
When I'm here,
I start being so creative

226
00:11:13,224 --> 00:11:15,813
because it
means something to me.

227
00:11:15,847 --> 00:11:17,504
It's a very quiet city

228
00:11:17,538 --> 00:11:19,920
but also there is something
, you know?

229
00:11:19,955 --> 00:11:21,853
Something that you have
the feeling

230
00:11:21,888 --> 00:11:25,236
you want to be a part of,

231
00:11:25,270 --> 00:11:28,377
and I think that's why
many people come here.

232
00:11:28,411 --> 00:11:30,828
There's no past.
There's only a future.

233
00:11:30,862 --> 00:11:32,001
- Mm.
- In a sense.

234
00:11:32,036 --> 00:11:33,831
You can create
your own world here.

235
00:11:33,865 --> 00:11:36,350
Yeah.
Exactly, yeah.

236
00:11:39,388 --> 00:11:39,888
♪

237
00:11:53,126 --> 00:11:54,886
You know, when I was a teenager,

238
00:11:54,921 --> 00:11:57,820
the... the real punk rockers
were like [inaudible] us,

239
00:11:57,855 --> 00:11:59,781
and we were like... so they would
all be like, "No, no, no."

240
00:11:59,788 --> 00:12:01,272
Punk's dead."

241
00:12:01,306 --> 00:12:03,930
By the time we go into it,
it was like [inaudible].

242
00:12:03,964 --> 00:12:05,966
Hi, everybody, this is Anton,

243
00:12:06,001 --> 00:12:08,831
and I'm gonna tell you about
what I did

244
00:12:08,866 --> 00:12:10,453
to make dinner.

245
00:12:13,180 --> 00:12:15,838
I used two legs of lamb.

246
00:12:15,873 --> 00:12:16,832
I need to get a paper towel.

247
00:12:16,839 --> 00:12:20,153
I washed them first,

248
00:12:20,187 --> 00:12:23,812
and I laid them down
on the cutting board

249
00:12:23,846 --> 00:12:25,468
and I stabbed them.

250
00:12:25,503 --> 00:12:28,920
♪

251
00:12:28,955 --> 00:12:32,510
And I sliced cloves of garlic

252
00:12:32,544 --> 00:12:37,446
into small slivers

253
00:12:37,480 --> 00:12:40,483
and I inserted those
into the holes.

254
00:12:40,518 --> 00:12:44,246
Then I rubbed the lamb
with olive oil

255
00:12:44,280 --> 00:12:49,492
and covered it in sea salt
and black pepper

256
00:12:49,527 --> 00:12:52,495
and then...

257
00:12:52,530 --> 00:12:55,360
I sliced potatoes

258
00:12:55,395 --> 00:12:58,156
and parsnips and carrots
and a little bit of onions

259
00:12:58,191 --> 00:13:03,023
and made a bed inside
a glass Pyrex dish

260
00:13:03,058 --> 00:13:06,820
and I stuck those in the oven,

261
00:13:06,855 --> 00:13:08,857
got them very hot for a second,

262
00:13:08,891 --> 00:13:12,930
and then I turned it
all the way down to about 125

263
00:13:12,964 --> 00:13:16,347
and I let it go.

264
00:13:16,381 --> 00:13:19,488
Anton Newcombe is a legend,

