00:28:15,417 --> 00:28:17,067
Well, what would you do if you
had a five-year-old brain?

599
00:28:17,074 --> 00:28:18,386
This is like...
Yeah.

600
00:28:18,420 --> 00:28:21,113
His synapses is going...

601
00:28:21,147 --> 00:28:21,647
♪

602
00:28:25,807 --> 00:28:27,913
Can we spend one second
with the records?

603
00:28:27,947 --> 00:28:29,431
Oh, hell yeah.

604
00:28:29,466 --> 00:28:31,399
The main thing that
I'm looking for is

605
00:28:31,433 --> 00:28:33,850
always Beatles in mono,

606
00:28:33,884 --> 00:28:36,197
anything in mono
from the '60s stuff

607
00:28:36,231 --> 00:28:37,301
for when I DJ.
Yeah.

608
00:28:37,336 --> 00:28:39,752
Okay, I'll get two records.

609
00:28:39,787 --> 00:28:42,203
Quick enough, right?

610
00:28:42,237 --> 00:28:44,826
Cool.
Thank you.

611
00:28:44,861 --> 00:28:47,104
He asked me for the...
For, like, the third time

612
00:28:47,139 --> 00:28:49,313
where I come from and he
remembers that I'm in a band

613
00:28:49,348 --> 00:28:50,867
and that I've
lived here for years

614
00:28:50,901 --> 00:28:52,075
and I see him every week.

615
00:28:52,109 --> 00:28:54,077
He's an interesting guy,
kind of.

616
00:28:54,111 --> 00:28:55,872
He tends to moan a lot.

617
00:28:57,114 --> 00:28:57,614
♪

618
00:29:14,062 --> 00:29:16,099
You know what
you're ordering for dinner?

619
00:29:16,133 --> 00:29:18,998
I think... I think German food.

620
00:29:21,104 --> 00:29:21,604
♪

621
00:29:30,285 --> 00:29:30,785
♪

622
00:29:35,049 --> 00:29:37,879
I'm assuming that most days

623
00:29:37,914 --> 00:29:40,364
you're working in the studio.

624
00:29:40,399 --> 00:29:43,126
Do you take days off
when you just do nothing?

625
00:29:43,160 --> 00:29:45,853
I should be doing that, see.

626
00:29:45,887 --> 00:29:47,889
But, yeah, I like to
create every day,

627
00:29:47,924 --> 00:29:49,442
and then sometimes
I'm just too tired.

628
00:29:49,477 --> 00:29:51,893
That's why my studio is
just always set up as a house.

629
00:29:51,928 --> 00:29:54,309
So I just go there
and lay on the couch,

630
00:29:54,344 --> 00:29:55,966
listen to records.

631
00:29:56,001 --> 00:29:57,623
Because the type of music
that I listen to

632
00:29:57,657 --> 00:30:01,627
keeps my mind-set
exactly the same endlessly

633
00:30:01,661 --> 00:30:03,836
so my month becomes like a day.

634
00:30:03,871 --> 00:30:05,838
And my... my sleep
becomes like a nap.

635
00:30:05,873 --> 00:30:07,944
I just pick it up
where I left off.

636
00:30:07,978 --> 00:30:10,187
So I can think on ideas

637
00:30:10,222 --> 00:30:14,191
on the back burner
of my mind for...

638
00:30:14,226 --> 00:30:15,641
For weeks, you know?

639
00:30:15,675 --> 00:30:17,850
It's like the...

640
00:30:17,885 --> 00:30:19,852
What they would call, like,
alpha wave generation.

641
00:30:19,887 --> 00:30:23,856
It's just like you keep yourself
going in the zone, you know.

642
00:30:23,891 --> 00:30:25,306
It's weird.

643
00:30:25,340 --> 00:30:27,653
Oh, no, that's him, actually.

644
00:30:27,687 --> 00:30:29,655
Yeah, it looks good.

645
00:30:29,689 --> 00:30:33,210
Super.

646
00:30:33,245 --> 00:30:35,661
I love this. This is
what I come to Germany for.

647
00:30:35,695 --> 00:30:38,491
They love it.
That's the real deal.

648
00:30:38,526 --> 00:30:40,977
Eisbein is pork knuckle,

649
00:30:41,011 --> 00:30:45,153
or more accurately,
a big freakin' shank.

650
00:30:45,188 --> 00:30:49,917
Unlike schweinshaxe,
its crispy roasted cousin,

651
00:30:49,951 --> 00:30:53,541
eisbein is brined, cured,
then boiled with spices

652
00:30:53,575 --> 00:30:55,888
until tender
and falling off the bone...

653
00:30:55,923 --> 00:30:58,166
♪

654
00:30:58,201 --> 00:31:02,032
Usually served with sauerkraut
and boiled potatoes.

655
00:31:02,067 --> 00:31:06,036
♪

656
00:31:06,071 --> 00:31:09,902
Schnitzel, pounded, breaded,
and deep-fried

657
00:31:09,937 --> 00:31:13,388
and served with brown potatoes
and creamed mushrooms.

658
00:31:16,115 --> 00:31:18,393
What do people like here?
I mean... or do you even know?

659
00:31:18,428 --> 00:31:21,396
Well, you know,
it goes from cheesy pop

660
00:31:21,431 --> 00:31:23,985
to rock, garage.

661
00:31:24,020 --> 00:31:26,056
People love techno.
It's known for techno.

662
00:31:26,091 --> 00:31:28,024
Yeah.

663
00:31:28,058 --> 00:31:31,717
And real ethnic
singalong get-drunk songs.

664
00:31:31,751 --> 00:31:34,064
Do you play locally?
Do you play here a lot?

665
00:31:34,099 --> 00:31:35,376
- No, no.
- No!

666
00:31:35,410 --> 00:31:36,722
You just...
You live and work here.

667
00:31:36,756 --> 00:31:38,413
You record here but you don't...

668
00:31:38,448 --> 00:31:41,554
I'm not interested
in it too much,

669
00:31:41,589 --> 00:31:43,660
'cause I have nothing to prove.

670
00:31:43,694 --> 00:31:46,076
I mean, I've been playing
since I was 11 years old.

671
00:31:46,111 --> 00:31:49,045
Do you... do you think you have
any responsibility as a musician

672
00:31:49,079 --> 00:31:52,427
other than to make
the best art you can?

673
00:31:52,462 --> 00:31:55,327
Well, I have self-set goals.

674
00:31:55,361 --> 00:31:58,088
I believe it's
the duty of older people

675
00:31:58,123 --> 00:32:00,573
to hold the torch just till
somebody gets it

676
00:32:00,608 --> 00:32:02,637
and then even older people can
look behind them and go,

677
00:32:02,644 --> 00:32:04,267
"Aw, somebody else got it.

678
00:32:04,301 --> 00:32:06,407
They're following
down the road."

679
00:32:06,441 --> 00:32:07,711
So that means like
an older writer

680
00:32:07,718 --> 00:32:09,617
can go, "Okay, all isn't lost."

681
00:32:09,651 --> 00:32:10,680
"It didn't end in the '60s.

682
00:32:10,687 --> 00:32:12,758
Here's this younger guy
who's 50."

683
00:32:12,792 --> 00:32:13,966
- Right.
- See?

684
00:32:14,001 --> 00:32:16,141
But it's my responsibility

685
00:32:16,175 --> 00:32:18,143
to hold that torch for other
people that are younger

686
00:32:18,177 --> 00:32:20,007
than me down the road.

687
00:32:20,041 --> 00:32:23,769
And even for the... the squares to
leave just this tangled mess

688
00:32:23,803 --> 00:32:26,668
of your art and ideas
and let people figure it out.

689
00:32:26,703 --> 00:32:27,773
Don't spell it out.

690
00:32:27,807 --> 00:32:29,292
Right.

691
00:32:29,326 --> 00:32:31,259
You know?

692
00:32:31,294 --> 00:32:33,158
But I love it up here.

693
00:32:33,192 --> 00:32:35,608
I think it's okay, 'cause
people stay out of my hair

694
00:32:35,643 --> 00:32:38,680
and you can be invisible.

695
00:32:38,715 --> 00:32:41,649
Well, that must be nice.

696
00:32:41,683 --> 00:32:43,789
Crazy, right?

697
00:32:43,823 --> 00:32:46,033
This is actually really good.
Mm.

698
00:32:46,067 --> 00:32:48,518
No human could eat all of this.

